**Abstract:**
Reading notes on Hans Frei's "Theology in a University" (from "Types of Christian Theology," 1992). The document examines the tension between theology as church training and theology as Wissenschaft in the Berlin university model. It traces the debate from Schleiermacher's view of theology and Wissenschaft as autonomous equals to Harnack's assertion of scholarly learning's priority. Key themes include the hermeneutical stance (sharing the world of discourse being studied) vs. purely objective historical method, and the question of theology's distinctive character within the university.

**AI Recommendation:** Important reading notes on Frei concerning theology as academic discipline; relevant to author's critique of theology as neutral science.

